In my own life, I saw how quickly expertise can be converted into digital systems. During a gap year, I watched my mother, who is an OB-GYN, help train AI models using knowledge built over years of medical practice. At the same time, I think about students spending years trying to enter institutions built around mastering that same knowledge through older pathways. That contrast raises a sociological question: when technology changes how expertise is stored and distributed, how do institutions decide which forms of training, authority, and legitimacy still count?

At the same time, digital tools are also making new forms of care and coordination possible, such as remote support systems that connect caregivers and patients outside older institutional models like nursing homes. That suggests technology is not simply destroying institutions; it is also creating pressure for new ones.

Digital networks also make it easier for small groups to coordinate resources, knowledge, and labor across distance. That means technology can increase dependence on large platforms, but it can also expand the capacity for local building and distributed action.





